<paragraph id="2D79EC5ABD35FF90948F335C73E9FB4F" blockId="15.[113,1089,1068,1604]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF90948F335C7328FBCF" author="MARSHALL G. A. K." box="[144,336,1068,1092]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="114 - 117" refId="ref12829" refString="MARSHALL G. A. K. 1928: On two new species of Curculionidae (Col.) from the Canary Islands. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 71: 114 - 117." type="journal article" year="1928">MARSHALL (1928)</bibRefCitation>
synonymised this species with 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9096AA335D765EFBCF" authority="(Rosenhauer, 1856)" baseAuthorityName="Rosenhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[693,1062,1068,1092]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretaceum">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9096AA335D713BFBCF" box="[693,835,1069,1092]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. cretaceum</emphasis>
(Rosenhauer, 1856)
</taxonomicName>
, a common Mediterranean species, and he was followed by 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF9096C4333C766BFBEF" author="LINDBERG H. &amp; LINDBERG H." box="[731,1043,1100,1124]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="1 - 97" refId="ref12680" refString="LINDBERG H. &amp; LINDBERG H. 1958: Entomologische Ergebnisse der finnlandischen Kanaren-Expedition, 1947 - 51. No. 14. Coleoptera Insularum Canariensium. I. Aglycyderidae und Curculionidae. Commentationes Biologicae 17 (1): 1 - 97." type="journal article" year="1958">LINDBERG &amp; LINDBERG (1958)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF90946E331C731FFB0F" author="BRITO M. C. &amp; OROMI P." box="[113,359,1132,1156]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="1 - 81" refId="ref12106" refString="BRITO M. C. &amp; OROMI P. 1986: Los Apionidos de las Islas Canarias (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea). Publicaciones Cientificas Excmo. Cabildo Insular de Tenerife. Museo Insular de Ciencias Naturales 1: 1 - 81." type="journal article" year="1986">BRITO &amp; OROMÍ (1986)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90956D331D7056FB0F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[370,558,1133,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90956D331D7056FB0F" box="[370,558,1133,1156]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">Lepidapion senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently regarded as a good species (ALONSO- ZARAZAGA 1990 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF90950133FC7032FB2F" author="MACHADO A. &amp; OROMI P." box="[286,586,1164,1188]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" refId="ref12791" refString="MACHADO A. &amp; OROMI P. 2000: Elenco de los Coleopteros de las Islas Canarias. Catalogue of the Coleoptera of the Canary Islands. Instituto de Estudios Canarios, La Laguna, 308 pp." type="book" year="2000">a, MACHADO &amp; OROMÍ 2000</bibRefCitation>
) and it has been recorded from La Palma, La Gomera and Gran Canaria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65DCBFD1BD35FF8F948F33BC7117FC5F" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" type="description">
<paragraph id="2D79EC5ABD35FF8F948F33BC764FFED8" blockId="15.[113,1089,1068,1604]" lastBlockId="16.[151,1127,219,980]" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">
However, examination of Wollaston’s only 
<specimenCount id="3BC027D3BD35FF90964A33BC7089FB6F" box="[597,753,1228,1252]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
(
<typeStatus id="F27D52F8BD35FF9096E233BC7125FB6F" box="[765,861,1228,1252]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">syntypes</typeStatus>
) of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90979B33BD71A2FB6F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[900,986,1229,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90979B33BD71A2FB6F" box="[900,986,1229,1252]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(a female in each of the BMNH and OUMNH collections) shows them to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9097F7339D7318FAAF" authority="(Wagner, 1914)" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9097F7339D72CAFAAF" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. canariense</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF9094A0327C7321FAAF" author="WAGNER H." box="[191,345,1292,1316]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="12 - 32" refId="ref13164" refString="WAGNER H. 1914: Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Gattung Apion Hbst. Munchener Koleopterologische Zeitschrift 4 (1): 12 - 32." type="journal article" year="1914">Wagner, 1914</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. It would appear that the incorrect synonymising (
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF90976E327C7665FAAF" author="MARSHALL G. A. K." box="[881,1053,1292,1316]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="114 - 117" refId="ref12829" refString="MARSHALL G. A. K. 1928: On two new species of Curculionidae (Col.) from the Canary Islands. Tijdschrift voor Entomologie 71: 114 - 117." type="journal article" year="1928">MARSHALL 1928</bibRefCitation>
) of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90946E325D72B1FACF" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[113,201,1325,1348]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90946E325D72B1FACF" box="[113,201,1325,1348]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF909519325D73E9FACF" baseAuthorityName="Rosenhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[262,401,1325,1348]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretaceum">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF909519325D73E9FACF" box="[262,401,1325,1348]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. cretaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has led subsequent authors to regard 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90973C325D7103FACF" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[803,891,1325,1348]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90973C325D7103FACF" box="[803,891,1325,1348]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9097B0325D7639FACF" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[943,1089,1325,1348]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9097B0325D7639FACF" box="[943,1089,1325,1348]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as distinct. In their key 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF90957A323C7029FAEF" author="BRITO M. C. &amp; OROMI P." box="[357,593,1356,1380]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="1 - 81" refId="ref12106" refString="BRITO M. C. &amp; OROMI P. 1986: Los Apionidos de las Islas Canarias (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea). Publicaciones Cientificas Excmo. Cabildo Insular de Tenerife. Museo Insular de Ciencias Naturales 1: 1 - 81." type="journal article" year="1986">BRITO &amp; OROMÍ (1986)</bibRefCitation>
distinguished 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9096F5323D7101FAEF" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[746,889,1357,1380]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9096F5323D7101FAEF" box="[746,889,1357,1380]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9097A7323D7638FAEF" baseAuthorityName="Rosenhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[952,1088,1357,1380]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretaceum">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9097A7323D7638FAEF" box="[952,1088,1357,1380]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. cretaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(then thought to be conspecific with 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9095F1321D703CFA0F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[494,580,1389,1412]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9095F1321D703CFA0F" box="[494,580,1389,1412]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) on characters of the scutellum. The single large tubercle which the scutellum bears is certainly characteristic of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90970C32FD71E4FA2F" baseAuthorityName="Rosenhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[787,924,1421,1444]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretaceum">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90970C32FD71E4FA2F" box="[787,924,1421,1444]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. cretaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the double tubercle (which is also subbasal, not central) is characteristic of Wollaston’s 
<specimenCount id="3BC027D3BD35FF9097BC32DC7639FA4F" box="[931,1089,1452,1476]" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
as well as a long series of 
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90959C32BD73E1FA6F" box="[387,409,1485,1508]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L.</emphasis>
‘ 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9095B832BD7064FA6F" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[423,540,1485,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9095B832BD7064FA6F" box="[423,540,1485,1508]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’ in the current author’s collection. The scutellum of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90946E329D72B0F98F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[113,200,1517,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90946E329D72B0F98F" box="[113,200,1517,1540]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9094C8329D7334F98F" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[215,332,1517,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9094C8329D7334F98F" box="[215,332,1517,1540]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) is raised at apex but flat in 
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90966B329D71BCF98F" box="[628,964,1517,1540]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90966B329D7179F98F" baseAuthorityName="Rosenhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[628,769,1517,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretaceum">L. cretaceum</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF909715329D71BCF98F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[778,964,1517,1540]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">Lepidapion senex</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
also differs from 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF9094B6317D7357F9AF" baseAuthorityName="Rosenhauer" baseAuthorityYear="1856" box="[169,303,1549,1572]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cretaceum">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF9094B6317D7357F9AF" box="[169,303,1549,1572]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">L. cretaceum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having much less acuminate elytra and being smaller on average. 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD35FF9097F7317C72C3F9CF" author="WAGNER H." pageId="15" pageNumber="172" pagination="12 - 32" refId="ref13164" refString="WAGNER H. 1914: Beitrage zur Kenntnis der Gattung Apion Hbst. Munchener Koleopterologische Zeitschrift 4 (1): 12 - 32." type="journal article" year="1914">WAGNER (1914)</bibRefCitation>
, in describing 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD35FF90954D315D70E4F9CF" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[338,668,1580,1604]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="172" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense" subGenus="Lepidapion">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF90954D315D73EAF9CF" box="[338,402,1581,1604]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">Apion</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF909580315D7060F9CF" box="[415,536,1581,1604]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">Lepidapion</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF909638315D70E4F9CF" box="[551,668,1581,1604]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, compared his species with 
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD35FF8F97DF315D72C7FF7F" italics="true" lastPageId="16" lastPageNumber="173" pageId="15" pageNumber="172">A. acumina- tum</emphasis>
Schilsky, 1906 and 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F958C37AD70AFFF7F" authority="Wagner, 1908" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1908" box="[403,727,220,244]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvipilosum">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F958C37AD7043FF7F" box="[403,571,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">A. curvipilosum</emphasis>
Wagner, 1908
</taxonomicName>
, but not with 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F977937AD71C6FF7F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[870,958,221,244]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F977937AD71C6FF7F" box="[870,958,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">A. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which, in view of the only two Wollaston specimens being in British collections, he almost certainly did not see. The characters of the scutellum were not mentioned in Wagner’s description. Based on this evidence, 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F952F364D705EFEDF" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[304,550,317,340]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F952F364D705EFEDF" box="[304,550,317,340]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">Lepidapion canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is here regarded as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F97C7364D7657FEDF" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[984,1071,317,340]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F97C7364D7657FEDF" box="[984,1071,317,340]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D79EC5ABD2AFF8F94AA362C7369FD5F" blockId="16.[151,1127,219,980]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD2AFF8F94AA362C738BFEF8" author="LINDBERG H. &amp; LINDBERG H." box="[181,499,347,372]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" pagination="1 - 97" refId="ref12680" refString="LINDBERG H. &amp; LINDBERG H. 1958: Entomologische Ergebnisse der finnlandischen Kanaren-Expedition, 1947 - 51. No. 14. Coleoptera Insularum Canariensium. I. Aglycyderidae und Curculionidae. Commentationes Biologicae 17 (1): 1 - 97." type="journal article" year="1958">LINDBERG &amp; LINDBERG (1958)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD2AFF8F95E0362C708DFEF8" author="BRITO M. C. &amp; OROMI P." box="[511,757,347,372]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" pagination="1 - 81" refId="ref12106" refString="BRITO M. C. &amp; OROMI P. 1986: Los Apionidos de las Islas Canarias (Coleoptera, Curculionoidea). Publicaciones Cientificas Excmo. Cabildo Insular de Tenerife. Museo Insular de Ciencias Naturales 1: 1 - 81." type="journal article" year="1986">BRITO &amp; OROMÍ (1986)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD2AFF8F9734362C765FFEFF" author="GURREA M. P. &amp; SANZ M. J." box="[811,1063,348,372]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" refId="ref12406" refString="GURREA M. P. &amp; SANZ M. J. 2000: Endemismos de Curculionoidea (Coleoptera) de la Peninsula Iberica, Islas Baleares y Canarias. Universidad Autonoma de Madrid, Madrid, 384 pp." type="book" year="2000">GURREA &amp; SANZ (2000)</bibRefCitation>
associated 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F94C1360D7308FE1F" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1914" box="[222,368,381,404]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canariense">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F94C1360D7308FE1F" box="[222,368,381,404]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">L. canariense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
especially with the Valle de Masca – Teno Alto area of Tenerife, but it is rather more widely distributed, occurring at Santiago del Teide (
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F977D36EC7678FE3F" box="[866,1024,412,436]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="1998-02">February 1998</date>
and 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F902936EC72B6FE5F" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="2001-06">June 2001</date>
) and below Tamaimo (
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F95D436CC7004FE58" box="[459,636,443,468]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="1995-12">December 1995</date>
). It is also known from La Palma (
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD2AFF8F97E136CC734DFE7F" author="MACHADO A. &amp; OROMI P." pageId="16" pageNumber="173" refId="ref12791" refString="MACHADO A. &amp; OROMI P. 2000: Elenco de los Coleopteros de las Islas Canarias. Catalogue of the Coleoptera of the Canary Islands. Instituto de Estudios Canarios, La Laguna, 308 pp." type="book" year="2000">MACHADO &amp; OROMÍ 2000</bibRefCitation>
) where I have found it abundantly (Las Indias, Montaña de Abraham, Jeday, La Caldareta, and Roque Faro, 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F95F7368C7092FD9F" box="[488,746,508,532]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="1998-02" valueMax="1998-03-31" valueMin="1998-02-00">February – March 1998</date>
); Punta Sta. Lucia and Las Caletas, 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F9488356C7373FDBF" box="[151,267,540,564]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="2001-06">June 2001</date>
). Specimens taken at Epina, La Gomera, 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F96CC356C71DDFDB8" box="[723,933,539,564]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="1995-12-19">19 December 1995</date>
, 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F97AD356C761EFDBF" box="[946,1126,540,564]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="2003-01-10">10 January 2003</date>
and 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F94DB354C732FFDDF" box="[196,343,572,596]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="2008-04-27">27 April 2008</date>
constitute a new record for that island. The host is 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F976A354D7661FDDF" box="[885,1049,573,596]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Retama" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fabales" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="raetam">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F976A354D7661FDDF" box="[885,1049,573,596]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">Retama raetam</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, larvae feeding on the seeds. This plant has been recorded from all the islands except Fuerteventura, and as the weevil seems to occur wherever there is an abundance of the host it is likely to be widespread throughout the 
<collectingRegion id="EF0222B8BD2AFF8F95A735EC7061FD3F" box="[440,537,668,692]" country="Spain" name="Canarias" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">Canaries</collectingRegion>
. As stated above, all these records must now be referred to 
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F94AC35CD7369FD5F" box="[179,273,701,724]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F94AC35CD7376FD5F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[179,270,701,724]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">L. senex</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2D79EC5ABD2AFF8F94AA35AC7117FC5F" blockId="16.[151,1127,219,980]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">
It is perhaps surprising that Wollaston should have taken only 
<specimenCount id="3BC027D3BD2AFF8F975635AC719EFD7F" box="[841,998,732,756]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F901635AD7618FD7F" baseAuthorityName="Wollaston" baseAuthorityYear="1864" box="[1033,1120,733,756]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Lepidapion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F901635AD7618FD7F" box="[1033,1120,733,756]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">L. senex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and it may be that these were stragglers, since the species is usually common on its host. Be that as it may, his only specimens are the 
<specimenCount id="3BC027D3BD2AFF8F966A346C708FFCBF" box="[629,759,796,820]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" type="female">two females</specimenCount>
already mentioned, one in each of the BMNH and OUMNH collections. In order to fix the identity of the species the BMNH specimen is hereby designated the 
<typeStatus id="F27D52F8BD2AFF8F9619342C7010FCFF" box="[518,616,860,884]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="EAC697D9BD2AFF8F9696342D71B8FCF8" authority="Wollaston, 1864" authorityName="Wollaston" authorityYear="1864" box="[649,960,859,884]" class="Insecta" family="Apionidae" genus="Apion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="senex">
<emphasis id="1FB23048BD2AFF8F9696342D7172FCFF" box="[649,778,861,884]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="173">Apion senex</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD2AFF8F970F342C71B8FCF8" author="WOLLASTON T. V." box="[784,960,859,884]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" refId="ref13319" refString="WOLLASTON T. V. 1864: Catalogue of the Coleopterous insects of the Canaries in the collection of the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, 648 pp." type="book" year="1864">Wollaston, 1864</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and it has been so labelled (see above). In referring to what are presumably these 
<specimenCount id="3BC027D3BD2AFF8F9755340C719EFC1F" box="[842,998,892,916]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" type="generic">two specimens</specimenCount>
<bibRefCitation id="495791ABBD2AFF8F97F4340C72A7FC38" author="WOLLASTON T. V." pageId="16" pageNumber="173" refId="ref13319" refString="WOLLASTON T. V. 1864: Catalogue of the Coleopterous insects of the Canaries in the collection of the British Museum. British Museum (Natural History), London, 648 pp." type="book" year="1864">WOLLASTON (1864)</bibRefCitation>
stated that they were taken by him ‘on the mountains above Sta Cruz, in the island of Palma, during 
<date id="5978CA9ABD2AFF8F952C34CC73DFFC58" box="[307,423,955,980]" pageId="16" pageNumber="173" value="1858-05">May 1858</date>
’; the specimens themselves are unlabelled.
</paragraph>
